{"questionId":"27706","questionHtml":"<p>Show that the area of the quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADOE</mtext></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Note:</strong> In parts (a) and (b) of this question, candidates may consider either triangle AOD&nbsp;or triangle AOE&nbsp;and work correctly to obtain the answer. Side AD&nbsp;is interchangeable with side AE&nbsp;in the following MS.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>attempt to use right angled trigonometry or sine rule to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AE</mtext></math> in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mtext>AE</mtext></mfrac></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mtext>AE</mtext><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>-</mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>-</mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid approach to find the area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADOE</mtext></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo></math> area of triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AOE</mtext></math> OR area of triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AED</mtext></math> + area of triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>OED</mtext></math> OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>OE</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>AE</mtext></math></p>\n<p>Area&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADOE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>·</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>·</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>×</mo><mtext>AE</mtext></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>Area&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ADOE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27706","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.8a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the area of the quadrilateral ADOE is r2tan α.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}